        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-06-08T13:27:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "inputOffset represents the drawing offset in order to keep the pixels aligned with the original drawn content. input-\u003esubset().topLeft() represents the possible offset into the actual texture that needs to be taken into account for the sampling.\n\nIf we could use drawImageRect here, it\u0027d be basically:\n\n   SkRect srcRect \u003d input-\u003esubset();\n   SkR ect dstRect \u003d inputBounds; // (inputOffset and subset\u0027s width/height)\n   canvas-\u003edrawImageRect(input-\u003easImage(), srcRect, dstRect, kStrictConstraint);\n   \nSo we are mostly correct when input-\u003esubset().topLeft() is (0,0), which is the most common case. Off the top of my head, though, I don\u0027t remember a good way to test that this is working. I\u0027ve run into issue with it before but don\u0027t remember the exact circumstances.",
      "parentUuid": "a619bf8a_b333e355",
